<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="References">References</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Duration_(philosophy)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: References"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div class="mw-references-wrap mw-references-columns"><ol class="references">
<li id="cite_note-The_Creative_Mind-1"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-The_Creative_Mind_1-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-The_Creative_Mind_1-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">Henri Bergson, <i>The Creative Mind: An Introduction to Metaphysics</i>, pages 11 to 14.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-Henri_Bergson_pages_165-2"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Henri_Bergson_pages_165_2-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Henri_Bergson_pages_165_2-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">Henri Bergson, <i>The Creative Mind: An Introduction to Metaphysics</i>, pages 165 to 168.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-3"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-3">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/bergson/">The Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy</a> <i>Time and Free Will has to be seen as an attack on Kant, for whom freedom belongs to a realm outside of space and time.</i></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-4"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-4">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Parmenides, <i>On Nature</i>.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-5"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-5">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Aristotle, <i>Physics</i>, VI:9, 239b10.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-6"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-6">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Henri Bergson, <i>Matter and Memory</i>, pages 191 to 192.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-7"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-7">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Henri Bergson, <i>Time and Free Will: An Essay on the Immediate Data of Consciousness</i>, Author's Preface.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-8"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-8">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFBergson,_Henri2014" class="citation book cs1">Bergson, Henri (2014-06-03). <i>Time and Free Will</i>. p.&#160;122. <a href="/wiki/Doi_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="Doi (identifier)">doi</a>:<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://doi.org/10.4324%2F9781315830254">10.4324/9781315830254</a>. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/9781315830254" title="Special:BookSources/9781315830254"><bdi>9781315830254</bdi></a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Time+and+Free+Will&amp;rft.pages=122&amp;rft.date=2014-06-03&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.4324%2F9781315830254&amp;rft.isbn=9781315830254&amp;rft.au=Bergson%2C+Henri&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ADuration+%28philosophy%29" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-9"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-9">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/bergson/">The Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy</a> <i>For Bergson — and perhaps this is his greatest insight — freedom is mobility.</i></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-Creative_Mind-10"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Creative_Mind_10-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Creative_Mind_10-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Creative_Mind_10-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">Henri Bergson, <i>The Creative Mind: An Introduction to Metaphysics</i>, pages 164 to 165.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-11"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-11">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Henri Bergson, <i>The Creative Mind: An Introduction to Metaphysics</i>, page 163: <i>Strictly speaking they do not constitute multiple states until I have already got beyond them, and turn around to observe their trail. ... In reality, none of them begins or ends; they all dovetail into one another.</i></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-12"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-12">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Henri Bergson, Creative Evolution (1911) tr. Arthur Mitchell, Henry Holt and Company</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-13"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-13">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFDeleuze1989" class="citation book cs1">Deleuze, Gilles (1989). <i>Cinema 1: The Movement Image</i>. London and New York: The Athlone Press. pp.&#160;Page 5.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Cinema+1%3A+The+Movement+Image&amp;rft.place=London+and+New+York&amp;rft.pages=Page+5&amp;rft.pub=The+Athlone+Press&amp;rft.date=1989&amp;rft.aulast=Deleuze&amp;rft.aufirst=Gilles&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ADuration+%28philosophy%29" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-14"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-14">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFCanales,_Jimena2016" class="citation book cs1">Canales, Jimena (2016-10-04). <i>The physicist &amp; the philosopher&#160;: Einstein, Bergson, and the debate that changed our understanding of time</i> (Fourth printing, first paperback&#160;ed.). Princeton, New Jersey. p.&#160;4. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-691-17317-7" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-691-17317-7"><bdi>978-0-691-17317-7</bdi></a>. <a href="/wiki/OCLC_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="OCLC (identifier)">OCLC</a>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/942707420">942707420</a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+physicist+%26+the+philosopher+%3A+Einstein%2C+Bergson%2C+and+the+debate+that+changed+our+understanding+of+time&amp;rft.place=Princeton%2C+New+Jersey&amp;rft.pages=4&amp;rft.edition=Fourth+printing%2C+first+paperback&amp;rft.date=2016-10-04&amp;rft_id=info%3Aoclcnum%2F942707420&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-691-17317-7&amp;rft.au=Canales%2C+Jimena&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ADuration+%28philosophy%29" class="Z3988"></span><span class="cs1-maint citation-comment"><code class="cs1-code">{{<a href="/wiki/Template:Cite_book" title="Template:Cite book">cite book</a>}}</code>:  CS1 maint: location missing publisher (<a href="/wiki/Category:CS1_maint:_location_missing_publisher" title="Category:CS1 maint: location missing publisher">link</a>)</span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-15"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-15">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFCanales,_Jimena2016" class="citation book cs1">Canales, Jimena (2016-10-04). <i>The physicist &amp; the philosopher&#160;: Einstein, Bergson, and the debate that changed our understanding of time</i> (Fourth printing, first paperback&#160;ed.). Princeton, New Jersey. p.&#160;6. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-691-17317-7" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-691-17317-7"><bdi>978-0-691-17317-7</bdi></a>. <a href="/wiki/OCLC_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="OCLC (identifier)">OCLC</a>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/942707420">942707420</a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+physicist+%26+the+philosopher+%3A+Einstein%2C+Bergson%2C+and+the+debate+that+changed+our+understanding+of+time&amp;rft.place=Princeton%2C+New+Jersey&amp;rft.pages=6&amp;rft.edition=Fourth+printing%2C+first+paperback&amp;rft.date=2016-10-04&amp;rft_id=info%3Aoclcnum%2F942707420&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-691-17317-7&amp;rft.au=Canales%2C+Jimena&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ADuration+%28philosophy%29" class="Z3988"></span><span class="cs1-maint citation-comment"><code class="cs1-code">{{<a href="/wiki/Template:Cite_book" title="Template:Cite book">cite book</a>}}</code>:  CS1 maint: location missing publisher (<a href="/wiki/Category:CS1_maint:_location_missing_publisher" title="Category:CS1 maint: location missing publisher">link</a>)</span></span>
